Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

In this project, i will be analysing data associated with the TMDb Movie Data which contains informaton about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

Question(s) for Analysis¶

  1. Which genre has the highest and lowest budget?
  2. Which genre has the highest and lowest revenue?
  3. Which genre is profitable to invest in?

From the summary statistics, there are movies with a minimum runtime of 0 and a maximum runtime of 900 minutes which is interesting. Movies also have np.nan budgets and 0 revenues amounts. The period for this data analysis spans from 1960 to 2015. More that half of the movies in the data set have a popularity of below 1%. However, the maximum popularity is a little over 32%.

In [27]:
# function to plot the result of the group column for analysis
def graph(df, x_axis, y_axis,stat='mean',figsize=[24,6], color='red'):
    return df.groupby([x_axis])[y_axis].agg(stat).plot(kind = 'bar', edgecolor='black', figsize=figsize, rot=0, width=0.8, color=color );
In [28]:
# formtting the graph for the relationship between genre and budget
graph(df_split, 'genres', 'budget_adj', color='brown')
plt.xlabel('Genres', fontsize=16, weight="bold")
plt.ylabel('Budget', fontsize=16, weight="bold")
plt.title('Genre with highest and lowest Budget', fontsize=16, weight="bold")
plt.legend(loc='upper right');

The bar chart shows that Adventure Genre has the highest budget whilest that of TV Movie has the lowest budget.

Conclusions¶

The most profitable genre for one to invest in is Adventure. This is because it has the highest revenue as well as the budget. TV Movie Genre has the least budget as well as revenue whereas Foreign Genre is the lowest profitable genre.

The limitation is that some of the columns had null values. These missing values would have been difficult to obtain so they were filled in by the means of the respective columns.
